e Promised Land. Both Israelis and Palestinians claim the Jordan as a necessary boundary of an indivisible homeland. Examining the Hebrew Bible alongside ancient and modern maps of the Jordan, Havrelock chronicles the evolution of Israel’s borders based on nationalist myths while uncovering additional myths that envision Israel as a bi-national state. These other myths, she proposes, provide roadmaps for future political configurations of the nation. Ambitious and masterful in its scope, River Jordan brings a fresh, provocative perspective to the ongoing struggle in this violence-riddled region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aReligion. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  ariver jordan, borders, holy sites, sacred, religion, christianity, judaism, israel, palestine, miracles, divinity, scripture, pilgrimage, geography, bible, folklore, middle east, homeland, conflict, war, gaza strip, belonging, possession, dispossession, nationalism, jewish state, promised land, nonfiction, history, violence, moab, politics, political science, diaspora, book of joshua, prophecy, baptism, maps, mapmaking, cartography, peace park.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226319599423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226319599/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles